ce:section.ce:para:
To comparatively investigate the electrochemical performance of GCE, BP-GNMs, and BP-GQDs towards purine metabolites, CV experiments were conducted with 300 μM of each of X, Hx, and UA in pH 7 PB solution, as depicted in Fig. 6B-D. In Fig. 6B, the CV response of GCE with individual analytes exhibited broad peaks for UA (Epa =420 mV) and X (Epa =920 mV), along with a notable anodic oxidation signal for Hx (Epa = 1.1 V vs Ag/AgCl; ipa = 12.3 µA) (Table 2
                        ), indicating good electrochemical performance with Hx compare with poor responses with the other two analytes. Extended experiments with the GCE/BP-GQDs resulted in a high background current with very poor electroanalytical performance were obtained for (Table 2) UA at UA at 350 mV, X at 670 mV, and Hx at 1.04 V vs Ag/AgCl (Fig. 6B), similar to the electrochemical response observed with the Fe(CN)6
                        3-/4− system. This observation ruled out the usage of BP-GQDs for the electroanalytical performance of purine detection in this study. Interestingly, when the same electrochemical experiment was performed with GCE/BP-GNMs, well-defined and sharp oxidative peaks were observed for UA at 350 mV, X at 700 mV, and Hx at 1.02 V, which is 150 mV, 90 mV, and 100 mV lower than the potentials observed on the unmodified GCE, respectively (Fig. 6D) (Table 2). Additionally, the GCE/BP-GNMs exhibited peak currents approximately 42 times higher for UA, 27 times higher for X, and 7 times higher for Hx compared to GCE's response. This indicates the superior electrocatalytic performance of BP-GNMs towards UA, X, and Hx oxidation. Furthermore, the peak separation between UA, X, and Hx was around 300 mV (BP-GNMs), which is significantly advantageous for the simultaneous detection of UA, X, and Hx.
